I agree it definitely focuses on the technology.  Consider it a &quot;practical&quot;
introduction to REST.  Like a hands-on physics lab to get your interested in
what Physics has to offer.



On Tue, Dec 22, 2009 at 12:58 PM, Story Henry &lt;henry.story@...&gt;wrote:

&gt;
&gt; On 22 Dec 2009, at 20:44, Noah Campbell wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt; Why not teach REST from a systems engineering perspective.  The
&gt; properties
&gt; &gt; that define a RESTful architecture are leveraged by tools like HAProxy,
&gt; &gt; Nginx, Squid, Varnish and various other intermediaries.  Once you have a
&gt; &gt; good working grasp on how caching, etags, HTTP methods and response codes
&gt; &gt; impact the entire system, then you can focus on building an app.  Being
&gt; able
&gt; &gt; to produce a service that fits into ecosystem becomes much more relevant
&gt; &gt; then trying to drag someone to the conclusion without a tangible example.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Just a thought.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; That&#39;s the technology, which of course has to be taught. But unless you go
&gt; all the way up to the semantic level, you won&#39;t understand why the
&gt; architectural decisions were taken.
&gt;
&gt; Henry
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt; -Noah
&gt;
&gt;

